    <h1>U.S. Sanctions on Iran</h1>
    <p class="lede">The U.S. government restricts most financial dealings with Iran. The rules are run by a U.S. Treasury office called the <span class="term" title="Office of Foreign Assets Control — the U.S. Treasury office that enforces sanctions">Office of Foreign Assets Control</span> (most lawyers call it <strong>OFAC</strong>). For most everyday situations — sending money to a parent in Tehran, holding a savings account in Iran, reporting it on your U.S. taxes — there are clear, legal paths. The rules are explained here in plain English.</p>
    <p class="updated">Updated as of April 30, 2026</p>
  </div>
</section>

