<section class="article">
  <div class="container-narrow">
    <article class="prose">

      <h2 style="border-top:none;margin-top:0;padding-top:0;" id="remittances">Sending money to family in Iran</h2>
      <p><strong>Yes, this is usually legal.</strong> The Treasury Department issues something called a <em>“general license”</em> — a standing permission slip you don’t need to apply for. As long as you send the money through a U.S. bank or a registered money-transfer service, and the money is for basic living expenses for a family member, it’s allowed.<sup>1</sup></p>
      <p>Some U.S. banks may still decline Iran-related transfers, even when they’re legal, because they want to avoid any sanctions risk. If that happens, try another bank or a registered money-transmitter. Keep documentation of who you sent the money to and what it was for.</p>

      <h2 id="goods">What about goods, gifts, or imports?</h2>
      <p>You generally <strong>cannot</strong> import goods from Iran or export goods to Iran without applying for a specific license from the Treasury Department. This includes carpets, art, antiques, and similar items.</p>
      <p>Inheritance of personal property from family in Iran is often allowed, but the transfer of funds or items may need Treasury approval depending on the value and timing. A sanctions attorney should review the specific facts before any transfer.</p>

      <h2 id="travel">Is travel to Iran legal?</h2>
      <p>U.S. sanctions law <strong>does not categorically prohibit</strong> U.S. citizens and permanent residents from traveling to Iran. Many Iranian Americans do visit family. However, certain travel-related transactions may need authorization depending on the purpose of the trip.<sup>2</sup></p>
      <p>The bigger concern is the State Department’s Level 4 “Do Not Travel” advisory and the risk of arbitrary detention by Iranian authorities. See the <a href="airports-borders.html#travel">travel advisory in Airports &amp; Borders</a> for the full caution.</p>

      <h2 id="fbar">What is FBAR? (Foreign-account reporting)</h2>
      <p>If you have <em>any</em> foreign financial account — in Iran or anywhere else — and the combined value crosses <strong>$10,000</strong> at any point during the year, you must file a yearly report with the U.S. Treasury called <strong>FBAR</strong> (FinCEN Form 114).</p>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-title">FBAR is not an Iran rule</div>
        <p>FBAR applies to every foreign country. A savings account in Canada or the U.K. triggers the same filing. It is not an extra burden placed on Iranian Americans. What <em>is</em> Iran-specific: certain property interests in Iran may be subject to separate Treasury reporting or blocking requirements. If you have accounts or property abroad, talk to a CPA or tax attorney with international reporting experience.<sup>3</sup></p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="banks">If your bank closes your account</h2>
      <p>U.S. banks <strong>cannot lawfully close an account solely because of national origin</strong> — that would be prohibited national-origin discrimination. However, banks have wide discretion to manage perceived sanctions or fraud risk and may close accounts citing those reasons.</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Ask in writing for the specific reason.</li>
        <li>If you believe national origin played a role, file a complaint with the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (<a href="https://consumerfinance.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">consumerfinance.gov</a>).</li>
        <li>Consult a civil-rights attorney.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="if-uncertain">If you are uncertain</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Consult an attorney who specializes in sanctions and export-control law.</li>
        <li>Check the Treasury Department’s OFAC website (<a href="https://treasury.gov/ofac" target="_blank" rel="noopener">treasury.gov/ofac</a>) for current regulations and FAQs.</li>
        <li>Keep documentation of every transaction involving Iran.</li>
      </ul>

      <details class="citations">
        <summary>Sources — U.S. sanctions on Iran</summary>
        <ol>
          <li>31 C.F.R. § 560.545 (humanitarian-transactions general license); OFAC FAQ on personal remittances; International Emergency Economic Powers Act (IEEPA), 50 U.S.C. § 1701 et seq.; 31 C.F.R. Part 560.</li>
          <li>OFAC does not categorically prohibit travel to Iran. See OFAC FAQ and 31 C.F.R. Part 560.</li>
          <li>31 U.S.C. § 5314 (FBAR filing requirement for foreign accounts exceeding $10,000); FinCEN Form 114.</li>
        </ol>
        <p class="small"><strong>Additional resources:</strong> ACLU Know Your Rights (aclu.org/know-your-rights); IALDF (ialdf.org); PAAIA (paaia.org).</p>
      </details>

